    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "17a9c8e0_e78d7bc6",
        "filename": "lucicfg/starlark/stdlib/internal/luci/rules/builder.star",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 94,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-01-09T03:01:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "builder_tags and swarming_tags would be used for disjoint sets of tags.\n\nin reality, swarming_tags are used ONLY for \"vpython:native-python-wrapper\" flag that enables something that Robbie knows about. This was meant to be a temporary switch during migration, but it was never cleaned up. I am not sure anyone actually uses swarming_tags to specify swarming tags, i.e. nobody cares about the tags of the underlying build tasks. I\u0027d rather remove this feature, i.e. hardcode \"vpython:native-python-wrapper\" in starlark, so that configs always have it. +Robbie, how hard would be to make \"vpython:native-python-wrapper\" a default, so we don\u0027t have bring this here?\n\n\u003e When we introduce builder tags, will we be able to say that \"all builder tags are passed to Swarming as swarming tags unaltered\"?\n\nnot sure what you mean. If we introduce builder tags, they would not propagate to builds and tasks. They would remain a property of the builder definition, so they would not propagate to swarming.",
      "parentUuid": "891106f0_4ecc03e2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 94,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 94,
        "endChar": 8
